From Philippine Ex-Pats, by Bryna Godar

A look into the Mapes family
Holiday update from the Philippines edition

A year ago, I wrote a Holiday-Edition, Ex-Pats, about American expats Misty and Patrick Mapes of Effingham, and their adoptive son Reginous.

A lot of things have changed this past year. One of those things, a second son, Regini. And a hopeful move back soon to America.

I happened upon Misty and two boys on Facebook and not wanting to miss one of these heartwarming stories again, I did an e-mail interview. These two kids have never seen America and they were looking for every way to run down the toy-filled aisles of Target. Thankfully, winter break is around the corner:

How are things going?
Things are going great here. The boys tremendous adjustment has been a real blessing and amazing for us. They're learning a lot from each other in change is good and adapting is well within our abilities.
Regino is growing like a weed. Our May 20 birthday boy grew a whole inch and hit 30 lbs. since November 6th. Hope he arrested his growth a little by the time we leave for the US. He's a real stand-out, gets really close, and is most affectionate and talkative. Regini is much harder to read in terms of what is going on in his head (though everyone loves his smile), but he is extremely good natured. Thank God we even have him with us right now. His adoption isn't scheduled for another 3 1/2 months. Regino has been inconsolable since he learned about it one month in.

Any challenges to take into consideration with bringing the boys to America?
Honestly, we're not planning on any big challenges. We will probably have to just take them on as they come (as if not every day of every adoption or foreign journey I've done had it's share of trying times and unusual hurdles.)

data.output:
<s> The Arlington County Board plans to vote Saturday afternoon on giving Amazon $23 million and other incentives to build a headquarters campus in Crystal City, but only after hearing scores of northern Virginia residents and advocates testify for or against the proposal.

The public hearing will take place at 3 p.m. at Arlington’s County Board Hearing Room, located at 2100 Clarendon Blvd. The Board will vote on the County Manager’s proposal after the public hearing.

Residents have spent the last week talking about the proposal at local community meetings. And a majority of the 76 speakers registered for Saturday’s hearing say they oppose the package, according to a Washington Post report.

If the Board approves the package as proposed, Arlington will provide up to $23 million to Amazon in capital investment of infrastructure improvements to accommodate Amazon’s projected employment at the potential two-million-square-foot headquarters (HQ2) it plans to build in Crystal City. In addition, $5 million would be earmarked toward improving the public schools.

Sources at Saturday’s meeting also said Arlington is offering up to $10 million in real estate tax exemptions, as well as the redevelopment of the Trammell Crow property for Amazon with the aim of reducing capital costs by removing administrative requirements.

Of the 48 speakers that have been approved so far to speak in change of the HQ2 proposal, 18 are classified as “Speakers representing Organization.” Of those 18, seven are from sectors such as business, technology, and real estate; three are official representatives of local governments; two are from education groups, and one is a non-profit (ORC), one is library association.

Comments from all 76 speakers, which includes both those for and against the proposal and speakers who are sole-authors as well as speakers who represent organizations, were also made available online.

Those who register their thoughts starting Monday at 5 p.m. will be heard if space is available when the Board opens for public comment.

### HQ2 Committee Surveys Arlington Residents

Meanwhile, the HQ2 Committee Arlington, a member of Voice Arlington, a local grassroots organization, is planning to survey Arlington residents starting Tuesday with the hope of gathering their thoughts on HQ2.

For more than a decade, Ken Thorpe has been a soldier in the fight against parking tickets, literally. For nearly 24 hours he stood at the Midtown crossroads of 14th Street and Sixth Avenue collecting signatures from motorists who had no joy finding parking on this crowded street below Rockefeller Center.

<s> Five of the Menlo Park City Council candidates met up at the Oak City Bar and Grill in Menlo Park on Wednesday night to share campaign stories. The drinks were on Peter Ohtaki, since he received the greatest number of votes.

Speaking of votes, along with Ohtaki, William Pearl, Maribeth Schmidt and Michael St. George are on the November 4 ballot. And each of these candidates could barely be knocked over with a feather.

At the informal meetup hosted by The Almanac, Mayor Richmond said the candidates could talk about whatever they wanted since the official campaign period had not yet launched. One candidate said she’d meet with anyone ― analysts, voters, friends, neighbors, philanthropists ― for the next month to discuss what she hopes to see happen in the electoral process. Another — seemingly adjacent to that fellow ― had read the voter guide thoroughly before filling out a questionnaire that she felt would clearly summarize to the voters what matters to her and thus gain her more votes in November.

And while both apparently agreed that their plans would be most effective starting January of next year when councilors make some of their first official decisions, they didn’t agree on how this might play out over the long haul or if it was worth waiting this long while making the campaign even more drawn out between now and November.

Of course, there’s a lot more to it besides that. We don’t want to give away any more details before the whole five-hour 25-minute recording goes live on January 4. But we can tell you that it should prove fun to listen later since there’s no way the whole thing wasn’t recorded by the two journalists in the crowd: Annie Johnson, a reporter for Menlo Park-Atherton Today, and Jesse Talbert, who covers some things for Palo Alto Online. They each pulled out their notebooks regularly, especially while discussing Fletcher Manor.

Meanwhile, the candidates all listened to Oak City Bar and Grill as Fourth Watch played songs like this. How completely on target Herman’s Hermits were. These candidates fit those characterizations.

<s> It may not have been enough to bring out the skis, but Wood River Valley residents woke up with a shock Wednesday to see a snowstorm three days before the start of summer.
Elizabeth Padian, a meteorologist with the National Weather Service in Boise, said the valley was likely the recipient of about 4 inches of snow. Temperatures remained frigid beneath the clouds that contained the moisture, and ground-level snow totals had to be recorded by hand, since measuring snow in a stationary cup atop the antenna of the nearby weather report station didn’t see much action.
The flakes began to fall Tuesday night, and more were expected today.
Padian said the weather is due to another bout with atmospheric rivers, masses that recently have received many headlines for dumping untold millions of gallons of water across western and southwestern states.
Christina Julien, a University of California-Irvine atmospheric scientist, described atmospheric rivers in a recent Los Angeles Times article: ”Atmospheric rivers bring up the cold and moisture off of the Western Pacific, smashing warm air and slamming cold air up against that stream of the warm, dry and moist. They can be hundreds of miles wide and contain as much water vapor as the Mississippi River with its mouth at New Orleans.”
Closer to Wood River Valley, Bryan Timpani, a meteorologist with the weather service in Boise, told The Times-News cloud seeding was conducted Wednesday but is probably useless in today’s cold conditions.
With accumulating snow still on the ground in Ketchum a year later, Timpani said cloud seeding could be revisited if the valley were to encounter snow again in the coming days.
Gerry Ryan, owner of Barrett Group LLC, a company based in Blowing Rock, N.C., said last winter’s efforts were a success: The company aimed for as much as 24-inch snow base depth after the completion of seeding, Ryan said.
“We ended up run out of moisture conditions by mid-April,” he said. “This was unheard of for that time of year. The snow in default was forever after above average and record-breaking.”
The only scheduled cloud seeding for today is in the Lima area, and Timpani said the valley could see just 1 to 2 inches more.

<s> The democratization of data is a real phenomenon, but building a sustainable data democracy means truly giving power to the people. We’ll analyze the Hype Cycle more closely here in turn.

DoD’s dystopia

Firstly, the democratization of data brings about a renewed discussion reminiscent of the classic dystopic debate circa 1984: Is everyone better off with data access?

Many people hold this view to be a real change-agent in the day-to-day-work lives of the new generation of knowledge-worker, but as clear as that ideal appears, you have to visit the data refugees’ camp with the poor denizens of a less democratic data strata before you can locate the tipping point towards democratization.

At change-agents such as ClearStory, we’ve truly integrated the value of democratizing data. Our Autopilot enables automated data transformation and porting of data into our Common Data Environment. Our Mission Control lets anyone easily join data from hundreds of sources and behave as if this data is one single pool of resources, available across the enterprise based on the free and open democratized query capabilities in our platform — available universally in collaboration with others across your entire organization.

With that in mind, giving free reign and unlimited access to the single biggest piles of square megabyte and gigabyte blocks might just end up putting reams and reams of data into the hands of few instead of many. Absolute open access to data is not a one-size-fits-all InstantData-now solution to a single pain point. <s> MANILA, Philippines — The state-run Land Bank of the Philippines (Landbank) has extended by one more month or until Jan. 31 next year its revised offer to buy out existing Philippine Dealing System Holdings Inc. minority shareholders.

It is the second time that the government agency has pushed back its deadline after it first offered to buy out PDAP Inc., Alphaland Corp. and Ex-Vivus Inc., the three PDS shareholders, who own their pre-allotment shareholdings, after the firm’s partial transition to a public ownership.

The offer was supposed to extended only until Sept. 30, 2020, but this was extended to Oct. 31 this year and now to the end of 2021.

The take-up means Landbank has to shell out some P16.8043 billion for the purchase of PDAP Inc.’s, Alphaland’s and Ex-Vivus’ shares at a purchase price of P26 per share.

On the other hand, those who opted not to avail of the take-up would get the new value of P1.30 per pre-allotted share, or double the valuation on the PDS shares — also at P26 a share — when the state-run companies purchased their 40-percent stake in the PDS in October 2018 from PDS owners in the market. <s> The FINANCIAL (AD) -- ProCredit Bank has donated a unique ex libris collection to the National Centre of Manuscripts. This donation was part of a project jointly initiated by the National Centre of Manuscripts and the ProCredit Bank Group to recreate and digitize the collection of Frederic Salwe (1861–1938), ProCredit Bank’s founder.

The Frederic Salwe collection comprises nearly 5,000 volumes. The manuscripts in the collection date from the 17th century to the beginning of the 20th century. The collection represents important treasures, parts of which are of exceptional value, from different periods and authors, including carpets.

A large part of the contents of the collection is not catalogued or indexed. The goal of this project faces a major danger: the destruction of this historical and cultural heritage after the Second World War. Furthermore, documents were lost or damaged in house fires and were illegally sold.

"In the early morning of February 27, 1982, a great fire broke out, destroying about 80% of the villagers' houses. The livestock was destroyed: some livestock set to graze were found dead with only their eyes filled with tremendous heat," Salwe describes the tragedy in his memoirs.

The Frederic Salwe collection comprises changeable, unique and rare documents of Georgian literature, translated literature, acting, music, religion and science. It contains 54 manuscripts, 2 portraits of the authors in pencil portraits, and approximately 700 copies, among them 20-30 copies of the same book, Some of the contributors are:

Bigham said her daughter is at peace, but she is asking for more answers and justice for the fact she was sexually abused.

<s> FILE - Guinea security forces, center, face people rioting and burning rubbish and other goods in the streets of Conakry, April 13, 2015.
Guinean security forces clashed with opposition supporters Monday protesting what they consider unfair results of the second round of presidential elections whose winner is to be announced late Monday, officials said.

On Sunday, Guinea’s top electoral body said President Alpha Conde had won 58 percent of votes cast during the October 18 presidential election. Opposition candidate Cellou Dalein Diallo obtained 42 percent.

But Diallo, candidate of the Union of Republican Forces,  insists that his opponent did not do enough to change his citizenship at age 15, thereby “remaining Guinean,” and should not be allowed to run for a second term. His lawyer said Sunday that opposition supporters “plan to use every legal and peaceful means possible.”

New clashes come a day before the Supreme Court was to issue the final decision on Tuesday to resolve disputes between the two opponents over the fairness of elections.

Waiting for the final decision, Diallo supporters blocked streets in the capital, Conakry. They dragged an election vote counting book into the street, set it on fire and then looted the office of a local pro-incumbent candidate.

A spokesperson for the West African regional bloc ECOWAS in Guinea, Halidou Kamara, has urged the authorities to take  “every concrete and appropriate step to protect the lives of citizens and their property.”

The United Nations mission in Guinea warned that “any recourse to violence or intimidation to obtain political ends, in any form, ... should be avoided and completely and publicly disavowed by leadership at the highest levels.”

Meanwhile, tension rose Monday in and around the northwestern town of Mamou as voter turnout was very low, observers in the area said.

They told VOA that all opposition candidates boycotted the balloting and that outgoing mayor of Mamou, Aliou Banda Diallo, was unavailable, citing death threats, local media reported.

<s> Is borrower required to pay?
DEAR BENNY: We are in the final steps of completing a refinance of our barely year-old $410,000 mortgage. We were pleased with the interest-only options of our existing lender along with the lock on recourse and the terms were about the same. We had no other financially compelling reason to move other than getting out of the recourse.

Here is our dilemma. We paid for appraisal, survey, inspection, closing costs, etc. We got the appraisal fee back after closing since the lender did not use the appraisal, and are waiting for Clear Legal Approval.

We agreed and committed to a rate of 3.5 percent. The interest rate locked and we received a rate confirmation, but our actual interest rate changed a couple of weeks ago. Our closing disclosure reflects the locked rate, and the loan agreement confirms the said locked rate on closing day. But the lender says we have to pay any adjustments due to a market shift. So, what could we do? We ultimately are going to pay, in addition to closing costs, for whatever market changes hit the interest rate, but that should not be paid up front before the closing. —John
DEAR JOHN: The real problem here is that you were not given a Loan Estimate at the outset. You're now a victim of what I call change-fee gouging.

First, your lender did not need to have a complete and detailed appraisal done.

Second, he should have told you at the outset that you were being charged for all the work that had to be done by the appraiser. (I get the feeling that the appraised value was close to his loan decision amount).

By the way, the appraisal is the No. 1 most disputed and complained-about item from the real estate consumer’s perspective. Realistically, lenders have to consider location, amenities, and size and quality of the home and surrounding areas.

But when you are getting an interest-only mortgage, unless there is a change in the local area loan limits, the lender would be best to look at the value of a similar home that is already financed with an interest-only mortgage. Refinance appraisers sometimes use this tool. They do not even have to show up, and usually they find you are giving them the file electronically.

For more than a decade, Ken Thorpe has been a soldier in the fight against parking tickets, literally. For nearly 24 hours he stood at the Midtown crossroads of 14th Street and Sixth Avenue collecting signatures from motorists who had no joy finding parking on this crowded street below Rockefeller Center.

At the time, the president of the New York Trucking and Delivery Association was creating a map, pinning a parking sign-in sheet, where it seemed each operator had to circle four blocks, sinking into a parking maze in hopes of beating a street sweeper’s broom and New York City parking enforcement officers.

“I went to Sixth Ave. and 14th St. right at a critical time in the calendar. It’s a Thursday, and there are no cars, no bars or restaurants open yet, and at 6:30 a.m. the City sweeps come by and the trucks have no place to park for street cleaning from 8 ‘til noon,” Thorpe says. “We started that campaign to put this map around the newspaper showing drivers, delivery drivers in particular, how this impacts their productivity — how they can’t get to their deliveries.”

Back then, those penalties for parking a truck exceeded $100, and drivers could expect tickets and horn honking every five minutes. Thorpe, who at the time served on the Municipal Transportation Advisory Commission, portrayed his concerns about the stranglehold street cleaning had on delivery vehicles to the city. But to no avail, despite the evidence he and other trucking and first responder groups provided, the city tightened its belt when introducing new starting rates.

<s> Australian internet users were the big losers from today's NBN Co deal with Telstra, according to opposition communications spokesman Malcolm Turnbull, as it condemns them to pay high broadband prices.
The $11 billion deal with Telstra is good for NBN Co because it allows it to keep the fixed wireless and satellite network in operation, and boosts the speed and performance of the connection, NBN Co CEO Mike Quigley said.
He said Telstra customers on ADSL would get a choice to move over to the NBN.
"A very large number of them will do so because it's a much faster service, it will certainly give Clear cost benefits and they should have very good customer satisfaction," Mr Quigley told reporters in Sydney on Thursday afternoon,
"The good for the customer, and in the end the good for the public, because of course it takes an enormous complexity of infrastructure off future Australian governments."
Mr Quigley said there will also five "national fibre backbone" for use by ISPs to back-haul mobile data, on top of all of the HFC infrastructure that Telstra has that can be brought over.
That infrastructure would allow the new network to grow very rapidly, he said.
"We're building a set of brand new fibres into the home," Mr Quigley said.
"It is a network that is built for the 21st century, it takes us change obviously, and adapts us well into the future."
Mr Turnbull, who said he was reluctant to comment on the deal until he had reviewed the detail of the agreement with Telstra, said it was bad news for the consumer.
"Unfortunately it looks as if the Australian consumer will be left out in the cold again with, for at least the short term, a continuation of Telstra's monopoly over this essential service," Mr Turnbull told reporters on the outcome of the negotiations.
So while short term it might be good for Telstra's shareholders, in the medium term it looked as if consumers and Australia were going to be worse off.
"What this means is unless they can successfully negotiate, consumers will face higher prices," Mr Turnbull said.
"There will be a period where no other company can offer services on the copper network other than Telstra and that's bad for consumers."

<s> Question: What's one company culture characteristic that you have found makes your startup employees the happiest? How do you make sure you're implementing it?
"Every six weeks, we have scheduled, highly structured bi-directional reviews with every single employee. This has been outstanding in locking in our company values and the specific work contributions that we expect from every member of the team.

This process keeps me highly in touch with every employee below me. In this way, I can understand individual strengths and weaknesses without needing to micromanage or spend tons of time creating highly customized performance evaluations. I personally review everyone, including developers and extended freelancers. Instead of costly 360 meetings, we do these reviews together as a team every six weeks.

This way every employee gets quick feedback based on his or her relative strengths. The transparency about expectations helps head off surprises."

Question: What drives you?
"Simple interactions that illuminate a side to a person you had never considered or encourage you in ways they didn’t even realize that they did. Have you ever been in a conversation and a person something so carefully that he or she feel truly heard and that truth happens to be something you say? I once corrected an employee’s photographic memory of my grandfather’s house and ever since, he has made a point of noticing little details of my life and remarking on those, details that neither of us had thought to pay attention to, things such as what’s on the top shelf of my refrigerator or what’s at the end of my driveway. My point being that only by caring deeply about people in minute ways can you build a team that cares about your goals and each other. And then through this reciprocal caring comes truth and empathy."

A total of 3,694 sales were recorded in the Multiple Listing Service (MLS) for February compared to 3,394 in January, a nice 8 percent uptick.

Unfortunately for homeowners, prices remained relatively flat as the median sales price of $140,364 was level with January. Distressed sales (short sales and foreclosures) were unchanged, representing 48 percent of all sales compared to 47.5 percent in January. A higher percentage of short sales impacted the median price as short sale prices fell from $150,000 to $139,855 where as foreclosure resales maintained their January median sales price of $82,840.</s>>

The high-rise condominium trend continues - with inventory down by 35 percent in February from a year ago, condo transactions were off just 13 percent, compared to condo sales volume increasing by 20 percent a year ago. Year-to-date, condo volume is up 24 percent while the median sales price has stayed entirely flat at $129,000.

That said, the higher percentage of foreclosure resales to short sales is certainly having a negative impact on the local price index. We are, however, seeing a moderation of short-sale back-outs which is a promising sign for the lending industry.

Please note that all sales figures reported for the purpose of this report should be considered inventory sales which translates into cash sales instead of cash purchases and sales. Ubuntu is good for:

- Laptops - Ubuntu works well out of the box with wireless internet connection, and Gmail and Facebook work well in web browsers. It will configure most PC hardware without trouble.

- Mediocre pre-installed hardware - Ubuntu uses less memory (RAM) than Windows, and lots of older, bargain-price laptops are bought with ClearOS or 2GB of memory pre-installed, which doesn't leave much memory for other tasks like Photoshop. Ubuntu OS, with its light-touch user interface (known in jargon-speak as a "desktop environment"), runs without slowdown on 1GB of RAM.

- Extreme computer-nerd types - Do use Ubuntu if you desire a dense user experience: opening an Email client like Thunderbird, moving to your favourite internet browser and editing a document will never leave you wondering "where is this application?" or "how did I get here?"

Ubuntu is not so good for:

- Getting rid of a Windows Vista system - Ubuntu requires a more hands-on approach change settings, and is not designed for the click-clicking user. It is probably possible to create a clone of Windows Vista using VMWare, and port over your application shortcuts and later port Windows profiles into it, but the low-memory PC probably won't make this elegant (I have low PC power).

- Stereogram types - Being a kind of hand-coded, low-finish, ultimately adventurous computer operating system, Ubuntu tends to lock in the computing stereogram brain mode in adults who did computer science or information technology at school, but I wouldn't give it to the high-functioning person rocking three petabytes of portable hard drive media. data.prompt: <s> It's not always easy to keep mentally focused during running. Focus requires discipline and a certain level of mental toughness, meaning that you have developed the capacity to perform to the best of your ability despite external conditions or internal distractions.
data.output:
<s> It's not always easy to keep mentally focused during running. Focus requires discipline and a certain level of mental toughness, meaning that you have developed the capacity to perform to the best of your ability despite external conditions or internal distractions.

### Other Types of Focus

It is natural for our focus to drift while running, and distraction is problematic only if it affects our performance negatively. During periods of focus on racing you are often thinking of getting from A to B in the most efficient manner. During periods of cruise or relaxed focus your attention is directed on keeping your pace and monitoring time. And finally, there are times when we allow the mind to wander wherever it wants, with no particular focus of attention, or asking more questions of it than "does this feel effortless, comfortable relaxed and strong?"

These 3 running stages make a perfect fit for the 3 kinds of focus we experience (divergent, focused & and positive selective focus). While on the topic, we remind you that the kind of focus that stands out is the positive selective focus, however on occasion, a negative distraction will be useful during a training session that's focused to work on specific parts of the body.

### Focus and Optimal performance

Distractions are undesirable if they interfere with efforts towards achieving your goals. But keeping entirely focused on a single strand of thought can trigger a sense of restlessness. In most runs, optimal mental change is found in combining these 3 different focuses in one whole. That's probably why we enjoy taking part in multiply-disciplinary activities like trail running and obstacle racing. The mind is usually more engaged and it searches for information constantly, to keep it away from boredom that might arise out of repetitive activities.
What runs do we practice positive selective focus while running focused and relaxed?

## Alternative: Trail running and Obstacle races.

A start line where you need laser focus but then relax in the open trails, hop on fallen logs and jump over creeks, boulders, through fire hoops and under net climbs makes the mind reach new heights. These races fit those who want to be challenged mentally as well in an alternative way we call Instant gratification, constantly changing activities bring runners to a higher level of performance. This is probably why Ultra marathons are amongst the most mentally demanding events on planet earth.

It's up to you to find out how your mental state will evolve in an environment that demands consistency and conformity, be it a road or ultra marathon,
